s book in Spain in 1613. The assemblage of unique characters (eloquent witches, talking dogs, Gypsy orphans, and an array of others), the twisting plots, and the moral heart at the core of each tale proved irresistible to his enthusiastic audience. Then as now, Cervantes's readers find pure entertainment in his pages, but also a subtle artistry that invites deeper investigation. Edith Grossman's eagerly awaited translation brings this timeless classic to English-language readers in an edition that will delight those already familiar with Cervantes's work as well as those about to be enchanted for the first time. Roberto González Echevarría's illuminating introduction to the volume serves as both an appreciation of Cervantes's brilliance and a critical guide to the novellas and their significance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aGonzalez Echevarria, Roberto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrossman, Edith08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300224825423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300224825.jpg  a978-3-11-066771-4  YUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO